tercession.—iacere‚ etc.: cf. Ep. XII. 3 eodem in loco iaceo, etc. The infinitives vexari, etc.,are exclama- tory. — qui ceteros, eto: the exe- cution of Lentulus and his fellow- conspirators, by which Cicero had saved Roman citizens from mur- der and arson, was the pretext for his banishment.

3. de domo: cf. Intr. 16.—-- illud doleo, eto: a common Latin idiom; cf. Att. 2. 24. 1 quas Nu- mestio litteras dedi, sic te iis evoca- bam. — negotium : tle. Cicero's recall. Mgrotimn with the force of res is colloquial, and frequent in all periods. Cf. the slang expression, ‘Tell me the whole business.’— mea vita: cf. note upon mea lux above. —— sine alios . . . susti- nere: Terentia proposed to 5611 her own property in order to raise money for the expenses attendant upon her husband’s recall. Cicero opposes this plan still more ur- gently in Fam. 14. 1. 5 quodad me.
